agraph","position":{"start":{"line":145,"column":1},"end":{"line":145,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As you can see from the plot above, the integrand and the importance sampling distribution are similar, which means that the importance sampling distribution is a good choice.","position":{"start":{"line":145,"column":1},"end":{"line":145,"column":1}},"key":"fvNnZj7psc"}],"key":"WPdugf4mtO"},{"type":"thematicBreak","position":{"start":{"line":147,"column":1},"end":{"line":147,"column":1}},"key":"JCa83Jezmv"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To use importance sampling, we need to modify the Monte Carlo integration code to sample points from the importance sampling distribution. The code to do this is shown below.","position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"key":"Sle0EX93JJ"}],"key":"W8kVZVFlul"}],"key":"o1XTx11aqZ"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"# Set the number of points to sample\nn_points_list = [100, 1000, 10000, 100000, 1000000]\n\n# Create lists to store the results\naverages = []\nstd_devs = []\n\n# Loop over the number of points to sample\nfor n_points in n_points_list:\n    x = expon.rvs(size=n_points, scale=1)\n    y = expon.rvs(size=n_points, scale=1)\n    z = expon.rvs(size=n_points, scale=1)\n    numer = psi_1s(x + 0.5, y, z) * psi_1s(x - 0.5, y, z)\n    denom = expon.pdf(x) * expon.pdf(y) * expon.pdf(z)\n    integrand = numer / denom\n    integral = 8 * np.mean(integrand)\n    variance = 8 * np.var(integrand)\n    averages.append(integral)\n    std_devs.append(np.sqrt(variance))\n\n# Plot the results\nplt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\nplt.errorbar(n_points_list, averages, yerr=std_devs, fmt='o-')\nplt.axhline(0.858385, color='black', linestyle='--', label='Exact Value')\nplt.xscale('log')\nplt.xlabel('Number of Points Sampled')\nplt.ylabel('Integral Value')\nplt.title('Overlap Integral of Two H 1s Orbitals (Importance Sampling)')\nplt.legend()\nplt.show()","key":"XRqJsdny46"},{"type":"output","id":"f6RFm_vdnnb4bIx8dNL21","data":[],"key":"moT7qUEh1W"}],"key":"k9BouDyaOY"},{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":184,"column":1},"end":{"line":184,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The plot above shows the value of the integral as a function of the number of points sampled using importance sampling. The exact value of the integral is shown as a dashed line. As you can see, the value of the integral converges to the exact value much faster using importance sampling compared to random sampling.","position":{"start":{"line":184,"column":1},"end":{"line":184,"column":1}},"key":"RLFrPjblEv"}],"key":"bdPxVKW6pK"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":186,"column":1},"end":{"line":186,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Summary","position":{"start":{"line":186,"column":1},"end":{"line":186,"column":1}},"key":"cKwIPdh9Dg"}],"identifier":"summary","label":"Summary","html_id":"summary","implicit":true,"key":"ef4KQe6zJr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":188,"column":1},"end":{"line":188,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In this lecture, we used Monte Carlo integration to calculate the overlap integral of two H 1s orbitals. We first used random sampling and then improved the efficiency of the calculation using importance sampling. We found that importance sampling converges to the exact value much faster than random sampling.","position":{"start":{"line":188,"column":1},"end":{"line":188,"column":1}},"key":"u6XLmX6itB"}],"key":"cCrdNcolZQ"}],"key":"lh6B7vfGhL"}],"key":"niLh3FNPLb"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}}}